The bone house fascinates yet after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi.
The toast resembles the back of a prehistoric Saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine, and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batllo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the premises the surname of House in bones.
Organic forms, wild colors, unusual use of stones, tile fragments and mosaic, reminding stairs and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for Antoni Gaudi’s New Art.
The front facade of the house unfolds its dreamlines, its pleasant colours and textures that recall nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see geometry, pace and order thought accurately.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colours is reinforced.
The winding and torsion of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood copies waveframes of windows, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, oilton and lamelles.
The Battlo house, which stands in the Eixample neighborhood in the Passeig de Gracia market street at number 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction was made for two years and the house ended in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another entirely new but quickly accepted Gaudi’s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-housing house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely about his project that the decorations were born for a representative apartment of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
For the facade, other artists and creators also worked.
The common work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and the Guell Park in which there are other works by Gaudi.
The locals called the hot house just after it finished because of its organic shapes "the house in bones".
Others, in view of the specific mechanism for opening the windows, called it "the house that dashes".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of St. George's boss of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motives.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with aerial windows and typical fireplaces.
Their inclination of 45 degrees seems weird.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not respect the construction guidelines of then and did not let himself be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city's construction permit, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finish the municipal council was horrified and requested changes.
For example, it did not like members of the municipal council that the pillars of the construction start on the public roadwalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) authorization to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a room and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented in a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house is shared by a staircase by which you access to an independent toast terrace.
All straight angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction received additionally new facades a non-traditional grill and two additional floors.
The Gaudi game with the light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with the light wells.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was just enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than the dark that, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to cross this step in 2002 on the 150th anniversary of the famous creator’s birth.
They continued the visits because they found that it is a profitable company and they expanded the field of visits to the common spaces and the attic, including toilet terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is not really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist cards holders have 20% discounts.
The sum is still above the entry price in the other buildings of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you need quickly to find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and completely visit the house.
