Devices to follow people are increasingly requested by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child brings more and more people to think of watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can also be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases such as that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of lighters but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of the little Anicka has excited a large number of people and they started looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even though the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We strive to tell everyone that it’s not spying, but just another way to reduce the probability that there’s another tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the Czech markets’ tracking devices suppliers.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I haven't encountered such cases yet."
“Most people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency case.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention that if the child doesn't want to carry something like this, he'll get rid of it.
“And even the smaller can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something expressly when they don’t want to be under control.”
"Mobile phones, which can cut up like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations," Bockova said.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is very questionable.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything so that the child doesn't have an electronic device that can locate it."
"This is the phone now."
"As the tracking devices will grow, they (the criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases the criminals will always be ahead of the police," the psychologist said.
It confesses, however, that such devices can help in an unprepared aggression by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, who offers tracking services for both cars and people, says that having such a device can help, even if it is destroyed in the case of an aggression.
"The device can be parametered in such a way that it is in regular emission after a given period."
“In the event that the device is destroyed, there is still the last position of the data subject.”
“The more expensive devices also have an inclination meter that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself in a lengthy position without moving,” said Cech.
According to him, the so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special prolog.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those that are wearing as a pendant of the size of a box of ignitions or to the smallest phone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
“This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device.”
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracing device is developed in the form of a bracelet or a pendant, it will always use the same technology as to trace cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in autonavigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alert the current position of a vehicle.
