A longer index than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the annular are exposed to a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men aged 60," co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University, said.
The finger could thus help determine which men should be subjected to prostate cancer test, especially by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the index of the right hand shorter than the annular.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had the fingers of the same length, we found the same likelihood of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular risk, however, fell to 33 percent, for men aged 60, the risk decrease reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of both cited fingers - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular the different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, renowned Czech genetician and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
