Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, just like that for private business.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in a large part of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarometer survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, he follows the changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements appear from the results of this year’s survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the rather sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the surrounding Pacific of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy has risen after it has suffered a strong decline in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which reduces the regional average (see Table 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents in the region declared satisfied with how their country's democracy worked in practice; it is the same figure as last year but with a strong increase on 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Approximately 34% said they had confidence in their country’s parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but heavily increased compared to 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America shaken support for democracy.
Although this did well during the global financial crisis, it was certainly due to the fact that many countries in America have only suffered a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty has only increased slightly in 2009 and has again declined to 32 percent this year.)
But the mood varies significantly from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is a widely shared feeling of progress.
This is rare in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and violent crimes have worsened.
It was only for the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem for their country (see Table 5).
