A microbe tolerant arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say that it shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This body has a double capacity."
"It can be developed either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That's why it's very special, even though it's far from being a truly "foreign" form of life, commented Paul Davies C. W. of the University of Arizona, co-author of the report in the online edition of Thursday's Science journal.
Six major elements have long been considered essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We are wondering what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of the State University of Arizona, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in researching life beyond Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, know what life looks like, Anbar says.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss this, which did not disclose the details of the find, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose an extraterrestrial life.
That wasn't the case.
"The discovery shows that in other planetary environments, organizations might be able to use other elements to actuate biochemistry and that the "standard" set of the elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, might not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute of Planetary and Spatial Science Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not a member of the research team.
“This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
It was not a casual discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono as it is equipped with high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; therefore, it speculated that a microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace each other.
“Arsenic is toxic primarily because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus.”
"Accordingly, organizations have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
“But arsenic is different enough to not work exactly as phosphorus; it enters inside and, somehow, goes the work of our biochemical machine,” Anbar said.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing arsenic concentrations to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, Deputy Professor of Microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
Arsenic was more common at the beginning of Earth’s existence, she said; thus, researchers issued the hypothesis that the first forms of life could have used it.
This suggests that there might be other ways to form life, not just how life on Earth was formed at the beginning,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
