After a campaign marked by invective and negative, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a forward-looking sign of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders on Tuesday did not produce any breakthroughs on major issues to be dealt with during the “lamed canard” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polished discussion about the differences of both sides and the recognition of their shared responsibilities to be governed, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score points.
The President’s deficit committee’s public meeting on Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that several months' close interaction has created mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap; but that, however, still divides members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both parties are now in a period of mutual trial and test in order to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while attempting to assess the boundaries of public opinion and voter patience for renewed partisan warfare.
This is why the Tuesday meeting and subsequent comments of the participants disclosed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid change in climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is tax, expenditure, health care or duties, both parties remain miles away.
