After the White House meeting on Tuesday, more optimism plans on a possible agreement on issues discussed during the "lamed canard" session, with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston, from the Brookings Institution, warned that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th congress will meet in January.
Instead, he said, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done will be, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to true cooperation.
“I consider most of what happens between today and 2012 as a pre-spectacular or shadow-boxing compared to the 2012 main event,” he said.
The reasons are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present in tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to meet their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the early reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Committee, including reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, removing retirement age and reducing expenditures.
Co-presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, according to themselves, imposed the issue of public agenda deficit in a way that cannot be ignored.
