The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected, which suggests that there are at least few reasons or willingness to compromise on tax issues today.
Galston plans two phases in the struggles between the White House and the Republicans of the Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of supporting confrontations, given that the Republicans dispute Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; to then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the supporting spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Anyone who will be judged in loss will have to change his way and find compromises.
But this would nevertheless be an optimistic point of view.
Partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there appears to be a greater ideological difference between Obama and the Congress Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, both parties’ activists see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more consequential election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort from both sides to find an agreement ground on the issues that still divide them.
