The European Union changes rules for obtaining visa
People must go to Visa Applicants Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to present themselves to the Visa Applicants Service Centers (ASC, according to their English-language signs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the biometric information of the applicant, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will provide certain advantages for applicants, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment for an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to present themselves at an interview with the Consular Representative; they will only present themselves at the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and take their footprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the AUC, applicants who wish a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 extra service rate.
For more information on the new procedure to apply for the visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
