A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancún a domestic, commercial and industrial lighting renovation plan in 100 countries in order to obtain a greenhouse gas reduction (GES) that corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction needed to be made to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding commitments to reduction by industrialized countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), most of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emitted on the planet would be light.
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
Last year in Copenhagen, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have committed to voluntary reduction plans that should increase overall GSE emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will need to remove this further 5 Gt balance sheet to stabilize the climate rise to 2 degrees centigrade by 2020 in order to prevent it from going out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy spending is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, this energy need is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6000 to 10000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week - this company has also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostates in addition to emitting very little heat.
They do not contain mercury.
Several specialists have posted reserves for fluo-compact bulbs as they contain mercury and need to be removed as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, the report indicates, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluo-compact bulb, but rather the coal thermal plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
Only in the United States, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants, the construction of which would cost it 2.5 billion.
