Climate: How France Budgets Its Promises of Financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to consider compliance with the promises of rapidly unlocked funding (that is fast start or early funding) made by developed countries.
And the large French bituillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries have committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million a year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU released the big game to persuade its partners from the reality of its commitment to fast-start funding: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, brochures distribution...
Transparency is appreciable and appreciated at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it released €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right path to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, "new and additional" in order to ensure that additional effort is made without being at the expense of the public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what “new and additional” means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
The European Commission, for example, considered 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of public development aid.
In contrast, France believes that funding for “all new projects” of 2010 is “new and additional”.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditures of previous years or at the overall level of public development aid.
Concretely, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to comply with its commitment to “new and additional” funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Once again, there is no rule and everyone chooses its calculation mode.
Some, like France, consider that €1 borrowed equal to €1 given.
Obviously, this is hardly justifiable: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some profitable investments (often projects related to emission mitigation based on more effective technologies), it is necessary to present an euro that will be recovered as equivalent to an euro that is given... At least, it should not be counted under its commitments than the cost of the loan for the lender country (the equivalent country).
But France has only done such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check itself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other words) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 euro to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice password tour!
In summary, in its fast-start financing, France operates double fraud: on the one hand on the evolution of action in time and on the other hand on the reality of financial effort.
Only spending 36.1 million euros, it is able to make it believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in consistency with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has done arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other member states continue to give if enough to loan?) and in negotiations since developing countries are not completely dup...
The early funding chapter is only a small, relative short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
But it could be another sand grain in the immense machine that is UNFCCC.
Let's hope that won't be the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn the lessons from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for the years 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of compliance with its commitments and equity with other countries in the European Union.
But above all, France could advance the discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter discussed today): we will not escape the issue of "additionality" or the way to account for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these challenges as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would be likely to increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in discussions.
